By Huang Sizhuo and Li Yulou, southern weekend journalists

Southern weekend intern, in Beichen, Yang Xilie

Editor in chief | Wang Tao

Unexpectedly, the welcoming ceremony for discharged patients in Xuzhou, Jiangsu Province, led to more people being quarantined.

On February 24,2020, after being discharged from hospital and quarantined for 14 days, Wang, a patient with new coronavirus infection, returned home with his family. Neighbors and streets held a welcoming ceremony for "strong feelings among neighbors. ". However, 26, two people's nucleic acid review results is one positive and one weak positive, again hospitalised isolation observation, the community unit building again closed, and the community 65 people need home isolation.

As of March 2, more than 47,000 patients had been discharged from hospitals in mainland China. According to the sixth edition of the Protocol issued by the National Health Commission, discharged patients are advised to return to the hospital for follow-up in the second and fourth weeks after discharge.

After the review of nucleic acid testing "Fu Yang" news continued to appear. Song Tie, Deputy Director of the Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said at a news conference on Feb. 25 that 14 percent of discharged patients in Guangdong Province were "Fu Yang. ".

The seventh edition of the treatment plan, released on March 4, also makes specific reference to the issue of Fuyang, to strengthen health management and isolation. The News is frightening: Does Fu Yang mean the healer is ill again? Are they still contagious? Is the new coronavirus GONNA go on forever?

When you get out of the hospital, you may not be cured, you may not be sure

The DNA and RNA are unique "ids" for most organisms, and the "ids" for the new coronavirus are pieces of RNA.

Just as forensic investigators can use DNA to find suspects in old cases, examiners can take samples from deep inside a patient's throat or anus and send them to the lab for testing, to determine if the patient is infected with the new coronavirus.

Therefore, a negative-positive nucleic acid test is one of the criteria for admission and discharge. However, the accuracy of nucleic acid detection is related to many factors, such as the collector, sample quality, kit type and so on.

In the case of a throat swab, the SWAB (a long white cotton swab) is carried deep into the patient's throat to extract secretions. During the collection process, patients may at any time because of the discomfort caused by cough, vomiting, wearing protective clothing slightly inconvenient to the collection personnel, it is to increase the collection difficulty.

The accuracy of nucleic acid testing was questioned in early February. Early false-negative patients in Hubei Province -- as reported by southern weekend -- were already suffering from severe clinical symptoms, but could not be seen because nucleic acid tests were negative.

As a result, Zhang Xiaochun, deputy director of the imaging department at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, openly questioned the reliability of using only nucleic acids for diagnosis. After that, the fifth edition of the diagnosis and treatment plan stipulated that the CT image should be regarded as the clinical diagnosis standard (only in Hubei Province) .

Based on this, the so-called "Fu Yang" may also be due to sampling errors, diagnosis and treatment plan for the discharge standard for two consecutive negative nucleic acid test, many doctors found that some patients test for the third time, or even the fourth time to test positive.

In fact, a negative nucleic acid test is not the only requirement for a patient to be discharged. In the diagnosis and treatment program, discharge criteria also include body temperature, lung imaging and other clinical indicators.

According to the NHK, a female tour guide was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia in a ŌSAKA hospital on January 29. She was discharged on February 1 after improving. She developed cough on February 6 and tested negative for nucleic acid. Throat Discomfort remained on the 19th and nucleic acid test was again positive on the 26th.

Japanese media revealed little information, if the Japanese tour guide is still in the hospital before discharge cough, refer to the Chinese treatment plan discharge standard "respiratory symptoms significantly improved, " may not meet the discharge standard. Such a "Fu Yang" may be a myth -- as if she was discharged from the hospital without a cure, only to be discharged early because the test paper was inaccurate.

Hong Kong has no official guidelines for setting discharge criteria. Professor Jin Dongyan, of the school of Biomedical Sciences at the University of Hong Kong, told southern weekend that the main medical decisions are made by clinicians and they are cautious about whether they can be discharged, so the number of discharged patients is not very large.

"None of the patients with positive nucleic acid conversion had progressive lung disease. "

Mount Lu, a virologist at Massachusetts State University in the United States, told southern weekend that official guidelines should only be used as a reference and laboratory specifications should not substitute for clinical performance, discharge or otherwise, the judgment should be made by the doctor who knows the patient's clinical condition best combined with the results of laboratory tests.

In the sixth edition, the requirements for respiratory symptoms and lung imaging are "significant improvement" . Cai Weiping, director of the Infectious Disease Center of the Eighth People's Hospital in Guangzhou, told southern weekend reporters that in order to facilitate front-line doctors to measure and judge more accurately, in Guangdong Province, it was further subdivided into pulmonary inflammatory image changes with at least 50% recovery.

In addition to the nucleic acid test for Fuyang, the patient's clinical symptoms and lung Ct. .

"from the follow-up in Guangdong Province, none of the patients whose lung condition was aggravated due to positive nucleic acid transfer, " said Cai Weiping, whose team's follow-up results showed that 42 percent of the patients who were discharged from the hospital had improved lung condition due to absorption, 42% of the population hasn't changed. No change meant that these patients "didn't get worse than they did when they left the hospital, but they absorbed more slowly, " while the rest "had completely absorbed the inflammation in their lungs by the time they left the hospital and are now clean. ".

There are also concerns that Fu Yang could mean that the human body has been reinfected with the mutated virus. A total of 104 new coronavirus strains isolated from different locations have been identified to be 99.9% homologous, the joint team of experts on new coronavirus from the whole genome sequencing in China said at a press conference on February 24, it is suggested that the virus has not changed obviously.

On March 4th a Chinese team published a paper saying that the new coronavirus had produced 149 mutations and two subtypes. On March 2, Brazilian researchers sequenced the virus in two Brazilian cases, which were also different from those found in China.

However, there is no consensus on the mutation of the new coronavirus.

In the absence of a mutation in the virus, Jin believes that with the exception of a very small number of people with immune deficiencies or weakened immune systems who may continue to carry the virus, the vast majority of patients can rely on their own immune system to completely eliminate the new coronavirus.

He also believes that "intermittent detox" is unlikely to happen, nor has it occurred in other acute viral infections. The new coronavirus is either removed or hidden deep in the respiratory tract, undetectable by a NASOPHARYNGEAL Swab.

Constantly adjusting the treatment plan, or can be added to the anal swab

With the increase in the number of discharged patients, combined with the recommendations of front-line doctors, the diagnosis and treatment plan is also constantly improved, strengthening the requirements for follow-up.

The criteria for discharge in the third edition of the protocol, issued on January 22, include "two consecutive negative nucleic acid tests for respiratory pathogens (at least 1 day between sampling) " , however, there was no explicit requirement for continued isolation or follow-up of discharged patients.

The News of the discharged patient, Fu Yang, can be traced back to January 31. Zhang Zhan, an associate director of the respiratory and Critical Care Medicine Department at Wuhan University People's Hospital, published a report on Wechat, which showed that more sensitive tests were used on two patients who met the discharge criteria and tested positive for nucleic acid.

Zhang's hospital then took the advice of front-line doctors and, after two negative nucleic acid tests, added "continue isolation for more than two weeks" .

Since then, the discharge of patients with the requirements for follow-up gradually strengthened. On February 17, the notice on follow-up of discharged patients with COVID-19 pneumonia issued by the General Office of the National Health Commission required, if necessary, a follow-up visit 2-4 weeks after discharge for a new coronavirus etiological test.

Two days later, the sixth edition of the medical treatment plan issued by the National Health and Health Commission recommended continued isolation after discharge and follow-up visits and follow-up visits to hospitals in the second and fourth weeks after discharge, but the specific items involved in the follow-up visits have not yet been made clear, and this requirement is only a recommendation, it's not mandatory.

Southern weekend reporters collected in Chengdu, Tianjin Fuyang case, it is in the sixth edition of the release, in the second week after discharge from the hospital in the follow-up found.

On March 4, the National Health Commission issued the seventh trial edition of the diagnostic and treatment protocol. The discharge standard is still 4, and the fourth one has been changed to "sputum, nasopharyngeal Swab, etc. " .

The interpretation document issued by the National Health Commission on the same day stressed that in view of the fact that a small number of discharged patients have retested positive for nucleic acid testing, in order to strengthen the health management and isolation of discharged patients, replace the words "14 days of self-monitoring of health status" with the words "14 days of isolation management and Health Status Monitoring" .

In addition to continued isolation and follow-up, Zhang told China News weekly that the standard of care should be changed from two consecutive tests to three. In Shanghai and Guangzhou, anal swab nucleic acid testing was added to the sampling method.

Generally speaking, the site of the anal swab collection is 2-3 cm inside the anus. If the anal swab is positive for nucleic acid, it means the patient has a stool sample containing the virus or virus fragments.

"The early stage of the disease is dominated by positive NASOPHARYNGEAL SWABS, and in the late stages of the disease, many people have positive anal swabs, " Cai said.

Compared with other coronavirus studies, this finding does not surprise Jin Dongyan, "in particular, SARS, there is indeed a part of the stool with the virus, anal swab positive situation. "

Jin Dongyan believes that the emergence of this situation and the special environment of the Gut, that is, the gut mainly rely on mucosal immunity to fight and eliminate the new coronavirus. Specifically, the major players are not IGM (the body's earliest antibody when stimulated by an antigen) and IgG (the antibody with the largest proportion of antibodies in the serum) , but IGA (the antibody secreted by the Mucosa that plays the most important role in mucosal immunity) , so the GUT will clear the virus more slowly, and it will take a while.

"Some people go on like this for up to a month. Based on previous studies of SARS in Hong Kong and the United States, the number of intestinal SARS virus effluents decreased gradually, but remained relatively high after 23 and 26 days, with one lasting as long as 69 days,"Jin said.

Professor Lu Hongzhou, the Communist Party secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Clinical Center for Public Health, suggested in an interview with China News weekly on March 3 that anal swab nucleic acid testing should be considered in the new treatment plan. He also said that because Shanghai's discharge standard is more stringent than the national diagnosis and Treatment Program, so far, Shanghai discharged patients have not recovered Yang.

Is the "Fu Yang" person contagious?

Cai Weiping noted that the new coronary patients, nucleic acid positive to negative for a long time, even if the pre-anal Swab has been negative twice, can not completely eliminate the later anal swab nucleic acid detection "Yang" phenomenon.

On February 29, Zhang Wenhong, director of the Infectious Diseases Department of the Mount Hua Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, told a media group that it was not surprising that the discharged patient had "recovered Yang" . The focus was whether he had re-infected others. "So far, there have been no cases of people infected with the virus spreading to others in the country. "

At a news conference held by the Guangzhou municipal government on February 25, Li Yueping, director of the ICU of the Infectious Disease Center of the Eighth People's Hospital of Guangzhou, also disclosed that during follow-up visits of discharged cases, 13 patients were found to have recovered from Yang, tested 104 close contacts, all negative.

Cai Weiping told southern weekend that the current new crown nucleic acid test is a qualitative test, not quantitative. He observed that positive test results in follow-up patients generally fell in the "gray zone" , or "suspicious positivity, " between negative and positive.

"This shows that these 'Fuyang' patients do not have a large amount of virus or are not complete viruses, " Cai explained.

On February 27th Jama, a leading medical journal, published an article by a team from Wuhan University's Jama between January 1st and February 15th, in south-central hospital to receive treatment of the 4 symptoms of mild to moderate infection of medical staff, there is also a phenomenon of Fuyang.

"A certain percentage of recovered patients may still be virus carriers, " it said.

The corresponding author, Xu Haibo, is the director of the Imaging Department of Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University and vice-chairman of the Neurology Special Committee of the Chinese Radiological Society. February 29, he explained to southern weekend reporters, virus carriers refers to the virus parasitic human body does not become ill or low resistance to the onset of disease, as well as whether to become infected or not to observe research proof, "It's not scientific to jump to any conclusions at this point. ".

However, none of the affected family members were infected, despite direct contact with family members after their discharge from the hospital, the article said.

"If a patient with a confirmed new coronavirus is truly clinically well, and his or her doctor fully agrees that he or she is well, there is no need to worry about whether or not he or she is going to contract the virus, " Mount Lu said.

To be on the safe side, in order to observe the infectivity of the patients with nucleic acid Fu Yang, measures were taken to continue to isolate and observe the discharged patients.

If local medical conditions permit, discharged patients will be concentrated in another hospital for observation because the hospital has a specially treated sewage system that minimizes the risk of infection, Cai said.

The antibody test helps doctors determine whether a patient is ready to leave the hospital

Cai Weiping, a veteran of SARS, was one of the first experts to suggest that SARS was not an infectious disease caused by chlamydia. He also had an antibody test in 2013 after contracting SARS, it turns out the antibodies are still in his system, protecting him.

To make the test more accurate, Jin Dongyan suggested that antibody reagents, if mass-produced, can use antibody reagents to help doctors determine whether patients meet discharge criteria. Because patients in the post-infection and recovery period, the corresponding antibody content in the body is higher, reagents can be more accurately measured.

Antibody detection is more direct than nucleic acid amplification, fluorescence and other steps. It's easier to sample, just draw blood.

Serological testing was also included in the seventh edition of the Protocol, which was published on 4 March. National Health Commission interpretation is, because the incidence of COVID-19-specific IgM antibodies more than 3-5 days after the positive, IgG antibody titer recovery phase than in the acute phase 4 times or more.

For those who test positive, there's no need to panic. Cai Weiping mentioned that workers who have more contact with wild animals can also find a higher positive rate if they test for some virus antibodies, which means some viruses have entered their bodies, but they didn't cause the disease or infect anyone.

Mount Lu has said bluntly that the so-called negative-positive test results being discussed now need to be carefully weighed in the absence of full quality control of the testing technology, Independent Third-party Certification, and incomplete information on many patients.

"I feel that every time coronavirus appears, it seems to be constantly adapting to the natural world and the human body. " In Cai's view, SARS is a "relatively stupid" member of the coronavirus, which basically disappears after only a few generations in the natural world, to be able to adapt to this environment. But the "enhanced" coronavirus, Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) , has been around since the first outbreak, and the new coronavirus is more virulent, more transmissible and less recognized by the immune system.

Tsai worries that the future threat of coronaviruses may be greater than this new one, so some forward-looking surveillance is needed. In other words, to continuously monitor some changes in the natural world of coronavirus, if it is found that some viruses have mutated and can bind to a receptor in the human body to cause disease, it may lead to a large-scale epidemic, scientific Research and medical and health institutions must be prepared accordingly.

(southern weekend reporter Wang Weikai contributed to this report.)
